\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 E-Prime Communication Guidance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The following guidance is advisory and supports the clarity objectives of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations Personnel may apply English Prime (E-Prime) principles in written communications —
 specifically,
 avoiding forms of the verb "to be" when greater precision or flexibility would benefit the communication.
 This practice reduces false certainty in service communications and naturally invites end-user confirmation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For example:
 "This appears to be resolved" or "This should be working now —
 please verify" invites the user to confirm,
 whereas "This is fixed" places the user in a position of either agreement or conflict.
 The goal is not to introduce ambiguity,
 but to invite collaborative confirmation and reduce premature closure of unresolved issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Disambiguation and Clarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall communicate in plain language accessible to non-technical County staff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall define acronyms and technical jargon before using them in end-user communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
When multiple questions are required,
 All Information Operations Personnel shall number them individually.
 Example:
 "1.
 When did the issue begin?
 2.
 What error message appears?
 3.
 Can you reproduce the issue consistently?" This format reduces missed answers and vague responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall avoid compound or binary questions that allow for ambiguous single-word answers.
 Example:
 "Can I come before or after lunch?" invites the response "Yes." The clearer form is "Can I come before lunch?
 If not,
 what time after lunch works for you?" The goal is not to talk down to users,
 but to provide prompts precise enough that their responses are actionable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Vendor and External Partner Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When communicating with vendors or external partners on behalf of the Department,
 All Information Operations Personnel shall maintain the same documentation and clarity standards as for end-user communications.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall confirm commitments made to vendors —
 including agreed timelines,
 approved scopes,
 or escalation acknowledgments —
 in writing and shall document them in the relevant work order or contract record.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall not communicate acceptance of deliverables,
 changes to contracted scope,
 or authorization of additional costs without IT Director approval in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Accountability in Language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall use precise language of personal and departmental accountability in service communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall use "I" when taking personal responsibility for a specific action or commitment.
 Example:
 "I will follow up with you by 3:00 PM today."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall use "We" when speaking on behalf of the Department as a whole.
 Example:
 "We received your request and are currently reviewing it."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall not imply action,
 approval,
 or authority beyond the scope of their assigned role.
 Commitments that exceed role authority shall be escalated to the designated authority as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 before being communicated to the user or vendor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Information Spillage Prevention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall not instruct or permit end users to transmit passwords,
 Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 or unprotected Personally Identifiable Information (PII) through standard work order notes or unencrypted email.
 If a user transmits such data into a work order,
 the receiving Information Operations Personnel shall immediately move the data to a Private Note,
 sanitize the user-facing record,
 and initiate the data spillage protocols required by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Identification and Reporting Procedures),
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 SI-12 (Information Management and Retention).
\end_layout

